commit.message: spd-say: Fix memory leak

pulse: Add feed_sync/_overlap support

With the full async interface we can control the draining: we let the
server buffer fill, and when draining ask the server about the playback
progression. The 20ms overlap should be enough to avoid move overruns.

pulse: Set prebuf to min_audio_length instead of tlength

We are actually fine with the server using a long buffer. What we
however want is for playback to start early. Flushing will discard the
long buffer anyway.

pulse: Restore using the full asynchronous pulseaudio API

Using the simple API is indeed simple, but does not provide flexible control
over audio writing, and can notably lead to underruns. This is
essentially the same as before, except that we keep writing audio data
as much as possible, since we can now control interrupting it from
spd_pa_simple_flush.

What we want is:

- Reduce server-side pre-buffering to min_audio_length
  - So playback can start as soon as reasonably possible without risking
    underruns
- Push as much data to the server as possible
  - So we avoid underruns
- Be able to stop as quickly as possible

Inlining the pulse simple implementation is not that complex and provides
best flexibility to achieve that.

That will also allow use to use pa_stream_get_time etc. to get the
playback position for proper indexing.

Fixes #885
audio: Also set loglevel of audio plugin running in server

Replace ctime with ctime_r

ctime is *not* thread-safe, so we could end up with assertion failure on
the ctime being empty.

generic: Fix documentation of GenericDelimiters and GenericMaxChunkLength

They were named so since the beginning.
Make sure to install the speech-dispatcher daemon
Fix format

Also load espeak-ng-fallback and dummy on autodetection

In case the user configuration breaks all modules, we will fallback to
espeak-ng without configuration, and at really worse, on dummy.

Make the fallback espeak-ng and dummy modules hardcoded

So that users cannot shoot themselves into the foot by only enabling a
module that happens not to be working.
spd-say: Avoid memory leak warning in lsansrc/clients/say/say.c
Advertise generic module error detection

core: Protect against unexpected output from module

The event-consuming thread would get stuck in pthread_cond_wait on
unexpected output if the main core thread is not actually waiting for
anything.

generic: Abort when speech failed

Otherwise if the speech command fails, the user just hopelessly gets no
speech any more, without speech-dispatcher falling back on something
that works.
generic: Simplify allocating the command string

Explicitly note that 0.12 is not released yet

Fixes #875

Add explicit note in README about creating new speechd modules
Fix build on non-Linux
